data.content:
## What happened

In C# 14 / .NET 10, **new span overload resolution rules** cause `array.Contains(num)` to bind to `MemoryExtensions.Contains<T>(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`. Expression trees cannot represent span-based methods, so compiling/interpreting the expression throws at runtime.

## How to fix

Cast the array to `IEnumerable<T>`, use `.AsEnumerable()`, or call `Enumerable.Contains` explicitly:

```csharp
// Option 1: Cast
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 2: AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 3: Explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

All three force the compiler to bind to `Enumerable.Contains`, which is representable in an expression tree.
